Here’s a clear, step-by-step example showing how unstructured text gets converted into structured data using your pipeline.

🔹 Example Input (Unstructured Data)

“Hey!!! I was running to https://example.com
 on 12/05/2024, and I bought 3 books. They were amazing!!!”

🔹 Step 1: Noise Entry Removal

Remove stop words, punctuation, URLs, and numbers.

Remove stop words: I, was, to, on, and, they, were
Remove punctuation: !!! , .
Remove URL: https://example.com
Remove numbers: 12/05/2024, 3

👉 Result:

“Hey running bought books amazing”

🔹 Step 2: Word Normalization
Tokenization

Split sentence into words:

[“Hey”, “running”, “bought”, “books”, “amazing”]

Option A: Stemming (faster, less accurate)

[“hey”, “run”, “bought”, “book”, “amaz”]

Option B: Lemmatization (slower, more accurate)

[“hey”, “run”, “buy”, “book”, “amazing”]

🔹 Step 3: Regular Expressions (Pattern Extraction)

Example patterns:

Extract verbs
Extract keywords
Identify entities

👉 Example structured extraction:

Action: buy
Items: book
Sentiment word: amazing
Activity: run
🔹 Step 4: Modified Taxonomy (Organizing into Structure)

Map extracted data into categories:

{
  "user_action": "buy",
  "activity": "running",
  "item": "book",
  "sentiment": "positive",
  "keywords": ["run", "buy", "book", "amazing"]
}

### BAG OF WORDS #####


Bag of Words (BoW) is one of the simplest ways to convert unstructured text into structured data. It ignores grammar and word order, and just counts how often words appear.

🔹 What is Bag of Words (BoW)?

BoW represents text as a frequency vector of words.

👉 In simple terms:

Take all unique words
Count how many times each word appears
Store counts in a structured format (like a table or vector)
🔹 Example (Step-by-Step)
🧾 Unstructured Data (Sentences)
“I love playing football”
“I love watching football”
🔹 Step 1: Noise Removal

Remove stop words like I

👉 Result:

“love playing football”
“love watching football”
🔹 Step 2: Tokenization

Split into words:

Sentence 1 → [love, playing, football]
Sentence 2 → [love, watching, football]
🔹 Step 3: Normalization (Stemming/Lemmatization)

Using Lemmatization:

playing → play
watching → watch

👉 Result:

Sentence 1 → [love, play, football]
Sentence 2 → [love, watch, football]
🔹 Step 4: Create Vocabulary

Unique words from all sentences:

👉 Vocabulary:

[love, play, watch, football]

🔹 Step 5: Create BoW Vectors

Count word frequency:

Word	Sentence 1	Sentence 2
love	1	1
play	1	0
watch	0	1
football	1	1
🔹 Final Structured Output
Sentence 1 → [1, 1, 0, 1]
Sentence 2 → [1, 0, 1, 1]

Each position corresponds to:
👉 [love, play, watch, football]
